What is noteworthy =E2=80=94 and certainly more relevant to the 3rd-party a=
pp shutdown than this tweet =E2=80=94 is this bit from New York Magazine=E2=
=80=99s cover story ( https://nymag.com/intelligencer/article/elon-musk-twi=
tter-takeover.html ) about Musk=E2=80=99s tenure to date:

At ten that same night, they told managers they should =E2=80=9Cstack rank=
=E2=80=9D their teams, a common but cold method of evaluation that forces m=
anagers to designate their lowest performers. Amir Shevat, who managed Twit=
ter=E2=80=99s developer platform and had led large teams at Amazon, Google,=
 and Microsoft, was perplexed. Every company did stack ranking differently.=
 Should they sort workers by seniority? Impact? Revenue generated? No one h=
ad an answer. =E2=80=9CThey said, =E2=80=98We don=E2=80=99t know. Elon want=
s a stack rank,=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D Shevat says=E2=80=A6

Leave aside the stack ranking bit; note Shevat=E2=80=99s job =E2=80=94 head=
 of Twitter=E2=80=99s developer platform. Then, from later on in the story:

The following week, on November 3, employees received an unsigned email fro=
m =E2=80=9CTwitter=E2=80=9D relaying that the time for layoffs had started.=
 By 9 a.m. the following day, everyone would receive a note telling them wh=
ether they still had a job=E2=80=A6The layoffs wiped out Shevat and his ent=
ire team.

In short, it appears that the decision to cut off third-party clients was m=
ade very early on; it just took until now to pull the plug. That doesn=E2=
=80=99t change much of my analysis from Monday, other than the assumption t=
hat this may be a sign that Twitter Blue is a failure (since it wasn=E2=80=
=99t wrapped into it); according to this timeline there isn=E2=80=99t any r=
elationship at all.

Secondly, Casey Newton and Zo=C3=AB Schiffer, two of the authors of the pre=
vious story, added this detail on Platformer ( https://www.platformer.news/=
p/extremely-hardcore-our-new-york-magazine ) :

We=E2=80=99re told that Twitter revenue on Tuesday was down 40 percent year=
 over year. And Musk=E2=80=99s first giant interest payment on the company =
is due at the end of the month ( https://www.ft.com/content/25f67d89-2940-4=
3b9-9a42-bfc34d262631 ).

That link is to a Financial Times story that reports that Twitter=E2=80=99s=
 first interest payment is due at the end of the month; most corporate bond=
s pay out interest every six months, but apparently some of Twitter=E2=80=
=99s debt has quarterly payments. Twitter did have $6 billion in cash in th=
e bank at the time of the acquisition, so I assume it will make the payment=
, but if that 40% decrease in revenue is true, things are pretty grim. I di=
d a very rough estimate of Twitter=E2=80=99s cost savings from its layoffs =
in this Daily Update ( https://stratechery.com/2022/disney-expectations-twi=
tter-expectations-silicon-valley-expectations/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSU=
zI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJ=
hdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJlbnQiOnsidXJpIjpbImh0dHBzOi=
