kZlLU9Vik-Br4LjoP0MYZH96ofNsLVPkZsU4MAAh_hJjAUIePrv-H2ZoTONb4QBKSEtwVwn9nxD=
HboFiveAP-pYAxeVCxbzVrCuoNspka7aTeclYFesRsV_MA ) :

These are very rough estimates, but I think it is reasonable to assume that=
 Twitter=E2=80=99s employee costs have been cut significantly, leaving its =
total annual costs at around $3.0 billion (excluding last year=E2=80=99s la=
wsuit settlement); add on the company=E2=80=99s reported $1 billion in inte=
rest payments and the company needs to come up with $4.0 billion a year in =
revenue. 2021 revenue, meanwhile, was $5.1 billion, and remember, Twitter h=
ad around $6 billion in cash pre-buyout. In other words, while I suspect Tw=
itter=E2=80=99s ad revenue has been impacted, it will take a pretty large i=
mpact to drive the company bankrupt.

Well, a 40% decrease in revenue is a pretty large impact; if true ( The Inf=
ormation reported the same ( https://www.theinformation.com/articles/twitte=
r-manager-daily-revenue-has-dropped-40-500-top-advertisers-have-left ) ), t=
hat implies that Twitter is on pace for around $3 billion in revenue, which=
 isn=E2=80=99t enough to cover its costs and meet its debt obligations. At =
the same time, as I noted there is still (presumably) some money in the ban=
k to cover the payments for now.

Azure and OpenAI
----------------

From Bloomberg ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-01-17/microso=
ft-azure-to-add-chatgpt-to-cloud-services ) :

Microsoft Corp. said it will add OpenAI=E2=80=99s viral artificial intellig=
ence bot ChatGPT to its cloud-based Azure service =E2=80=9Csoon,=E2=80=9D b=
uilding on an existing relationship between the two companies as Microsoft =
mulls taking a far larger stake in OpenAI. The software giant announced the=
 broad availability of its Azure OpenAI Service, which has been available t=
o a limited set of customers since it was unveiled in 2021. The service giv=
es Microsoft=E2=80=99s cloud customers access to various OpenAI tools like =
the GPT-3.5 language system that ChatGPT is based on, as well as the Dall-E=
 model for generating images from text prompts, the company said in a blog =
post. That enables Azure customers to use the OpenAI products in their own =
applications running in the cloud.

This news isn=E2=80=99t a big surprise =E2=80=94 access to OpenAI services =
have been in preview =E2=80=94 and is covered by Microsoft=E2=80=99s previo=
us agreement/investment with OpenAI, in which Microsoft covered nearly all =
of OpenAI=E2=80=99s training costs with Azure credits. As far as I know Mic=
rosoft is getting access to these services at no additional cost (i.e. it=
=E2=80=99s what Microsoft gets out of said agreement).

What this does highlight is a point I should have made in AI and the Big Fi=
ve ( https://stratechery.com/2023/ai-and-the-big-five/?access_token=3DeyJhb=
GciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpX=
VCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJlbnQiOnsidXJpIjpbIm=
h0dHBzOi8vc3RyYXRlY2hlcnkuY29tLzIwMjMvYWktYW5kLXRoZS1iaWctZml2ZS8iXX0sImV4c=
CI6MTY3NjY0MTQ5MCwiaWF0IjoxNjc0MDQ5NDkwLCJpc3MiOiJodHRwczovL3N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5=
LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZS9vYXV0aCIsInNjb3BlIjoiZmVlZDpyZWFkIGFydGljbGU6cmVhZCB=
hc3NldDpyZWFkIGNhdGVnb3J5OnJlYWQiLCJzdWIiOiJSc2V1WUU4amdIZVBwV0pmMWZBYjRDIi=
widXNlIjoiYWNjZXNzIn0.WvG7BKS2CbfWlbip5LuLcIb16wbybb_92NPIvm_jpU6shoyvklO6H=
PXQWHJbsZg6UxVOoVaKg6YiNZbAM9UHaBO0dcuYt9d6-C2pnHM8MqHc4k81CWZjX9kfgFlozf2d=
KSkbvH1N7Wu5kWKKofH0deRVYQc6sYKrzvpm5Ld5AsrFaPXL9T_8rLzikJ_EAT8H2XsiUVpaR5l=
4XrICEJynvp2gxFYX_BH0i1v6kQojRuDNMXizjWP3OsMjBo1dKxO9wB-n3gEjQwxBvW0wxcQM3m=
QiO11cuIjDXBAkOeSGzOs5CW1Vma4yApEliMZFuVFdiblJfC9vptoMoul-laC8jw ) : it see=
ms clear that OpenAI really is motivated by its stated mission of building =
AGI =E2=80=94 artificial general intelligence. That is the capability that =
would be so valuable it would justify OpenAI=E2=80=99s weird structure that=
 would pay back Microsoft=E2=80=99s investment and revert ownership to the =
OpenAI non-profit; if the best application of AI ends up being a component =
in other products then it seems perfectly willing to cede that long-term op=
portunity to Microsoft in exchange for the compute to pursue the ultimate g=
oal.

Apple and China
---------------

I did want to highlight this two part series in the Financial Times about A=
pple and China: Part 1 ( https://www.ft.com/content/d5a80891-b27d-4110-90c9=
-561b7836f11b ) is about how Apple came to be so enmeshed in China, and Par=
t 2 ( https://www.ft.com/content/74f7e284-c047-4cc4-9b7a-408d40611bfa ) is =
about Apple=E2=80=99s options going forward. Three quotes that I thought we=
re interesting:

First, from Part 1, about how Apple hasn=E2=80=99t harvested know-how, but =
in fact imparted it:

Over the past decade and a half, Apple has been sending its top product des=
igners and manufacturing design engineers to China, embedding them into sup=
pliers=E2=80=99 facilities for months at a time. These Apple employees have=
 played integral roles co-designing new production processes, overseeing th=
e minutiae of manufacturing until things were up and running, and keeping c=
lose tabs on suppliers to ensure compliance. Apple has also spent billions =
of dollars on custom machinery to build its devices, developing niche exper=
tise that its rivals did not even know about, let alone compete with. It ha=
s transformed the company and the country. =E2=80=9CAll the tech competence=
 China has now is not the product of Chinese tech leadership drawing in App=
le,=E2=80=9D O=E2=80=99Marah says. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s the product of App=
le going in there and building the tech competence.=E2=80=9D

Second, from Part 2, this bit about Apple giving up more control to Chinese=
 suppliers may help explain why the company seems to be immune from retalia=
tion from China:

Even as Apple is attempting to diversify its supply chain internationally, =
its ties to China are simultaneously becoming stronger. For years, the tech=
 giant has been establishing closer ties with mainland Chinese companies in=
 exchange for concessions to operate more freely. Cook even personally forg=
ed a five-year agreement in 2016 to spend more than $275bn to help advance =
China=E2=80=99s economy and workforce, according to specialist tech publica=
tion The Information=E2=80=A6

However, Apple risks losing some control over its production process innova=
tions with the =E2=80=9Cred supply chain.=E2=80=9D One reason is it no long=
er owns as much production machinery at its suppliers=E2=80=99 plants =E2=
=80=94 a strategy that gave the company unprecedented control over how its =
products were made. The value of Apple=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Clong-lived assets=
=E2=80=9D in China peaked in 2018, at $13.3bn, and in the years since has n=
early halved to $7.3bn. Former Apple engineers that spent time in China say=
 that after iPhone sales peaked in 2015 the company was happy to be more re=
liant on suppliers=E2=80=99 machinery to save costs.

This section also talks about how COVID made it impossible for Apple to con=
tinue its practice of sending thousands of engineers to China for weeks at =
a time, forcing it to give up control to Chinese engineers:

Two former Apple manufacturing engineers say the company=E2=80=99s Chinese =
engineers really stepped up and proved themselves. =E2=80=9CApple provided =
a training ground for Chinese manufacturing engineering that was second to =
none,=E2=80=9D one person says. Apple, in turn, raised their pay and has be=
en able to retain most of the team despite frequent recruiting efforts from=
 rivals. However, two people familiar with Apple=E2=80=99s operations say t=
hat giving up control risks slowing innovation and leaking intellectual pro=
perty. =E2=80=9CThe Cupertino guys stood back and let the Chinese take the =
lead,=E2=80=9D says one. =E2=80=9CThe Chinese guys completely control the p=
roduct now.=E2=80=9D

Third, also from Part 3, about why India is probably not the panacea it is =
being presented as, at least not yet:

But some supply chain experts argue that the growth numbers in iPhone =E2=
=80=9Cmanufacturing=E2=80=9D in India are more hype than reality. Most oper=
ations that suppliers have set up for Apple in India are known as FATP =E2=
=80=94 Final Assembly, Test and Pack =E2=80=94 a labour-intensive process p=
erformed with components largely flown in from China and then assembled mos=
tly by Taiwanese companies. Pegatron and Foxconn may be moving there, says =
Steven Tseng, tech analyst at Bloomberg Intelligence, but their suppliers a=
re not. =E2=80=9CThere is no supply chain in India,=E2=80=9D he says. =E2=
=80=9CThey have to import pretty much everything from China.=E2=80=9D

There is also a story in Bloomberg ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/article=
s/2023-01-18/apple-gets-boost-in-india-as-chinese-suppliers-luxshare-ningbo=
-given-clearance ) about some Chinese companies getting cleared to operate =
in India for Apple=E2=80=99s sake; it will be interesting if these supplier=
s end up playing the same role in India that Taiwanese suppliers played in =
China (which made Taiwan a whole lot of money). Apple would certainly prefe=
r that.

